nicknames Bello FiGo Gucci and Gucci Boy but the popularity of his videos caused that when people searched \"Gucci\" in Italian web search engines the first search engine results were about him instead of the Italian brand of fashion [[Gucci]]. This caused him to be sued by the company, then withdrawn following a consensual agreement with which Bello FiGo renounced the use of the name Gucci.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.giornaledibrescia.it/tempo-libero/bello-figo-voi-ridete-io-faccio-milioni-di-view-1.1836898|title=Bello Figo: \"Voi ridete, io faccio milioni... di view\"|date=6 March 2014|website=Giornale di brescia}}</ref>\n\nBello FiGo's songs are done in an intentionally poor style called \"trash rap\" because of the low technical-stylistic quality of his rap music accompanied by bizarre, surreal, satirical and often grammatically incorrect texts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ilfoglio.it/musica/2016/11/30/news/bello-figo-rapper-intellettuale-trash-108502/|title=Ascoltare Bello FiGo per capire i tic della politica (e il referendum)|website=Il Foglio}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.corriere.it/spettacoli/16_dicembre_06/fraintendimento-testi-satirici-rapper-ghanese-bello-figo-72485258-bb24-11e6-8d3b-c05118807aea.shtml|title=Il fraintendimento dei testi satirici del rapper ghanese Bello FiGo|first=Aldo|last=Grasso|date=12 May 2016|website=Corriere della Sera}}</ref> His music videos, published only on YouTube, have totaled millions of views (for example, the song \"Non Pago Affitto\" has as of January 2020 over 25 millions views)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ookGv44MMd4|title=Bello FiGo ft The GynoZz \u2013 Non Pago Affitto (SwaG NeGri) Stai Li A Pagare!!! ASSGARAA|last=Bello FiGo|date=23 October 2016|via=YouTube}}</ref> and have made Bello FiGo a phenomenon of the Internet in Italy.\n\nAfter the first songs, characterized mainly by topics of vulgarity and sexism, Bello FiGo took over from 2016, with the songs \"Sono bello come profugo\", \"Non Pago Affitto\" and \"Referendum Costituzionale\", a more political role, applying his style and its self-irony to the stereotypical arguments inherent in immigrants in Italy, described as being mostly nasty and delinquent. He also mocked, besides these stereotypes, various political figures. For this reason in 2016 he was defined by [[Rolling Stone]] music magazine as \"the most politicized artist in Italy\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.it/musica/news-musica/bello-figo-e-lartista-piu-politicizzato-in-italia/340465/|title=Bello Figo \u00e8 l'artista pi\u00f9 politicizzato in Italia|date=22 November 2016}}</ref> and between the end of 2016 and the beginning of 2017, it suffered several disputes and threats of violence, even of racist background, by groups and subjects close to the extreme right, that led to the cancellation of some of his concerts for fear of public tensions and disorders (in [[Brescia]], in [[Borgo Virgilio]], in [[Legnano]] and in Rome).<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.internazionale.it/opinione/christian-raimo/2017/02/01/bello-figo-rapper-razzismo | title=Il rapper Bello FiGo sfida i nostri stereotipi sull'immigrazione| date=February 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.vice.com/it/article/bello-figo-gu-chi-e-analisi | title=Una mattina mi son svegliato / O Bello Fi, Bello Fi, Bello Figo Gu| date=18 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://milano.corriere.it/notizie/cronaca/16_dicembre_27/minacce-morte-rapper-bello-figo-mantova-5c84c44a-cbac-11e6-8b9b-1b0efa3fb5ec.shtml | title=Minacce di morte al rapper Bello Figo Annullato il concerto di Capodanno| date=27 December 2016}}</ref> \nOn 30 April 2018 he published [[Swag negro. Non ce la fa nessuno]], an [[autobiography|autobiographical book]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.googleadservices.com/pagead/aclk?sa=L&ai=DChcSEwiL5-KA_tnfAhXCQ9MKHZ40DXkYABAAGgJ3Yg&ohost=www.google.it&cid=CAASE-RoTkgdSWALH2XsG5k82bzQNTs&sig=AOD64_3O0UGbDK7oUlm-1tS4xp8fPSh7AQ&q=&ved=2ahUKEwi-ld2A_tnfAhUuM-wKHcLDAR4Q0Qx6BAgGEAE&adurl=|title=Amazon.it: bello figo swag negro|website=googleadservices.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.ibs.it/swag-negro-non-ce-fa-libro-bello-figo/e/9788817101875 | title=Swag negro. Non ce la fa nessuno \u2013 Bello Figo \u2013 Libro \u2013 Rizzoli \u2013 Varia &#124; IBS}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.booktobook.it/libri/bello-figo/ | title=Bello Figo: Cosa aspettarsi dal suo primo libro, Swag Negro| date=8 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.lafeltrinelli.it/libri/bello-figo/swag-negro-non-ce-fa/9788817101875 | title=Libro Swag negro. Non ce la fa nessuno \u2013 Bello Figo \u2013 Rizzoli \u2013 Varia &#124; LaFeltrinelli}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://it.blastingnews.com/cultura-spettacoli/2018/05/swag-negro-non-ce-la-fa-nessuno-il-nuovo-libro-di-bello-figo-002554067.html | title='Swag Negro, non-ce la fa nessuno', il nuovo libro di Bello Figo| date=6 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019 Bello FiGo was denounced by the [[University of Pisa]] and its rector, Paolo Mancarella, that declared, after being contacted by the [[Agenzia Giornalistica Italia|AGI]], that the University would have done everything to defend its honour and reputation, because of a song about sex Bello FiGo has published on his official YouTube channel on 6 December 2019, \"Trombo a facolt\u00e0\", that was recorded inside the classes of economics of the University, which declared that its staff didn't know anything about it and didn't give its authorization to record the video.<ref>https://www.rollingstone.it/musica/news-musica/bello-figo-denunciato-dalluniversita-di-pisa-per-il-video-di-trombo-a-facolta/491586/</ref><ref>https://www.iltempo.it/cronache/2019/12/11/news/bello-figo-trombo-a-facolta-video-hot-universita-pisa-denuncia-modelle-1254077/</ref><ref>https://voxnews.info/2019/12/11/trombo-a-facolta-bello-figo-gira-video-sconcio-alluniversita-di-pisa/</ref>\nIn February 2020 he released the song \"CoronaVirus\" that got more than 4.5 milion views on YouTube.\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:FiGo, Bello}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian internet celebrities]]\n[[Category:Italian YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian emigrants to Italy]]\n", "name_user": "151.33.195.103", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bello_FiGo"}
{"title_page": "1st Aviation Brigade", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name=1st Aviation Brigade\n| image=1AvnBdeSSI.gif\n| image_size = 150\n|caption=\n|country=[[United States]]\n|allegiance=[[United States Army]]\n|type=Aviation brigade\n|branch=\n|dates=1966-1973<BR>1977-present\n|specialization=[[Aviation]]\n|command_structure=[[United States Army Aviation Center of Excellence]]\n|size=[[Brigade#Army|Brigade]]\n|garrison=\n|nickname= \n|motto= \n|colors= \n|march= \n|mascot=\n|battles=\n|anniversaries=\n<!-- Commanders -->\n|current_commander=Colonel Tammy Baugh\n|current_commander_label=\n<!-- Insignia -->\n|identification_symbol=\n|identification_symbol_label=Distinctive unit insignia\n|identification_symbol_2=\n}}\n\nThe '''1st Aviation Brigade''' commands three distinctly different battalions\u2014the 1st Battalion, [[13th Aviation Regiment (United States)|13th Aviation Regiment]]; the 1st Battalion, [[145th Aviation Regiment]]; and the 2nd Battalion, 13th Aviation Regiment, the former Unmanned Aircraft Systems Training Battalion at [[Fort Huachuca]], Arizona.\n\n==Vietnam==\n\nThe 1st Aviation Brigade traces its origins to the [[Vietnam War]]. In April 1965 the U.S. Army Aviation Brigade (Provisional) was activated with the existing [[13th Aviation Battalion|13th]], [[14th Aviation Battalion|14th]], [[52nd Aviation Regiment (United States)|52nd]], and [[145th Aviation Battalion]]s,<ref group=\"Note\">September 24th, 1963 brought to a close the 45th Transportation Battalion and gave birth to the 145th Combat Aviation Battalion.</ref> already in South Vietnam, reporting to it. In August 1965 it became the [[12th Combat Aviation Brigade|12th Aviation Group]], which then doubled in size and was used to form the 1st Aviation Brigade in March 1966.<ref name=\"1AVNB\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.1stavnbde.com/|title=Portal - 1st Aviation Brigade - U.S. Army, Vietnam|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401212829/http://www.1stavnbde.com/|archive-date=1 April 2016|access-date=12 May 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Dunstan, in ''Vietnam Choppers'' writes that the numerous independent aviation companies deployed during the war's early years had become difficult to move between sectors because they had developed 'individual means of operating in conjunction with the formations they supported.'<ref>{{cite book |last1=Dunstan |first1=Simon |title=Vietnam choppers: helicopters in battle 1950-1975 |date=2003 |publisher=Osprey Publishing |isbn=0850455723 |page=37}}</ref> Thus the brigade was formed to achieve standardization.\n\nBrigadier General [[George P. Seneff]], the Staff Aviation Officer at [[Military Assistance Command, Vietnam]] (MACV), became the brigade commander. Because the requirements varied in each part of Vietnam, the brigade tried to collocate one assault helicopter company with each U.S. brigade and in course of time each Republic of Korea brigade.<ref name=1AVNB /> The companies supporting [[Army of the Republic of Vietnam]] units were located in centralized positions to best provide support. The brigade assigned one combat aviation battalion headquarters in direct support of each infantry division and this battalion headquarters normally worked with that division no matter how many companies might be assigned for a specific mission. The Brigade [[Headquarters and headquarters company (United States)|Headquarters and Headquarters Company]] was located in Saigon from May 1966 until August 1967.  Then the HQ moved to [[Long Binh Post|Long Binh]] where it remained until Long Binh was closed in the early autumn of 1972. The HQ then moved to the MACV compound at [[Tan Son Nhut]], where it stayed until withdrawal.\n\nAt this time the 52nd Aviation Battalion supported the [[4th Infantry Division (United States)|4th Infantry Division]] in the highlands, the 10th Aviation Battalion supported the brigade of the 101st and the Republic of Korea division, the 11th Combat Aviation Battalion supported the [[1st Infantry Division (United States)|1st Infantry Division]], the 214th\u2014the 9th Division, and the [[269th Aviation Battalion]]\u2014the 25th Division. The 13th Battalion, which was later to become a full group, remained in the [[Mekong Delta]]. Two aviation groups\u2014the [[17th Aviation Brigade (United States)|17th]] and the 12th\u2014supervised the aviation assets in the [[II Corps (South Vietnam)|II]] and [[III Corps (South Vietnam)|III Corps Tactical Zone]]s respectively. The aviation group commander was also the aviation officer for the U.S. Field Force commander.\n\nDuring June 1970, the 1st Aviation Brigade reached its largest size, at which point it contained four combat aviation groups, 16 combat aviation battalions, and 83 companies totaling over 4,000 aircraft and 27,000 personnel.<ref group=\"Note\">Constituted 25 April 1966 in the Regular Army as Headquarters and Headquarters Company, 222d Aviation Battalion. Activated 25 May 1966 in Vietnam.</ref> The 34th General Support Group (Aviation Maintenance and Supply) was transferred to the control of 1st Aviation Brigade in November 1971 where it continued in operation well into 1972. On the signing of the cease-fire on 28 January 1973, the Brigade strength had been reduced to 5,000 personnel and 420 aircraft in four combat aviation groups. The brigade was returned to Fort Rucker, Alabama, on 24 March 1973, and was deactivated on 6 April 1973.\n\nAccording to Shelby Stanton's ''Vietnam Order of Battle,'' subordinate brigade units in Vietnam included:<ref>Stanton, ''Vietnam Order of Battle'', 1987, 109.</ref>\n*[[11th Expeditionary Combat Aviation Brigade|11th]], [[12th Combat Aviation Brigade|12th]], [[16th Combat Aviation Brigade (United States)|16th]], [[17th Aviation Brigade (United States)|17th]], [[101st Aviation Brigade (United States)|160th]], [[165th Aviation Group]]s\n*the [[164th Aviation Group]] was activated from the assets of a Provisional Aviation Group in the [[IV Corps (South Vietnam)|IV Corps Tactical Zone]] in 1968, and was located at [[Can Tho]] throughout its time in Vietnam. Its heritage appears to be carried out, since 1995, by the [[164th Theater Airfield Operations Group]] at [[Fort Rucker]]. \n*[[10th Aviation Regiment (United States)|10th]], [[11th Aviation Battalion|11th]], [[13th Aviation Battalion|13th]], [[14th Aviation Battalion|14th]], [[52nd Aviation Regiment (United States)|52nd]], [[58th Aviation Battalion|58th]], [[145th Aviation Battalion|145th]], [[210th Aviation Regiment (United States)|210th]], [[212th Aviation Battalion|212th]], [[214th Aviation Regiment (United States)|214th]], [[222nd Aviation Regiment (United States)|222nd]], [[223rd Aviation Battalion|223rd]], [[268th Aviation Battalion|268th]], [[269th Aviation Battalion|269th]],<ref>Note the 187 Aslt Hel Co served with this battalion March 1967-Apr 1971, before being transferred to the 11th Avn Bn., with which it served Apr 1971-14 Feb 72, inactivated that day. Stanton, Vietnam Order of Battalion, 113, 119.</ref> [[307th Aviation Battalion|307th]], [[308th Aviation Battalion]]s\n*PHANTOM, DELTA, CAPITAL, I Corps, BUFFALO Aviation Battalions (Provisional)\n*7th Squadron, [[1st Cavalry Regiment (United States)|1st Cavalry Regiment]], 1st Squadron, 9th Cavalry, 3-17, 7-17 Cavalry, all Air Cavalry Squadrons\n\n==Training formation==\n\nOn 18 February 1977 the brigade was reactivated at Fort Rucker as a training formation.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Williams |first1=James W |title=A History of Army Aviation |date=September 2005 |publisher=iUniverse |isbn=9780595810369 |page=136}}</ref>\n\nFamed [[Vietnam War]] combat veteran [[John Bahnsen]] commanded the 1st Aviation Brigade in the late 1970s and early 1980s.<ref>U.S. Army Aviation Center, [https://books.google.com/books?ei=4jjSUZraD4q80QGzw4C4Bw&id=MborAAAAYAAJ&dq=1st+aviation+brigade+bahnsen&q=bahnsen#search_anchor United States Army Aviation Digest], 1980, page 26</ref>\n\nThe 1st Aviation Brigade\u2019s primary mission has been to train and develop future aviation warfighting leaders. Including the lessons learned from deployed units, instructors and students write, review, and coordinate Army Aviation combined arms doctrine for aviation units below brigade level.\n\nThe course curriculum consists of a wide range of professional military education subjects, with emphasis on combined arms battlefield integration. The tactical training is further reinforced with state-of-the-art simulation, allowing students to assume various command and staff positions at all command levels while fighting simulated battles throughout a wide spectrum of tactical scenarios. Equally important is the initial entry training (IET) taught to entry level Aviation Branch Soldiers. IET teaches fundamental skills for U.S. Army personnel to perform their occupational specialties in an aviation unit.<ref name=\"rucker.army.mil\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.rucker.army.mil/pdf/InstallationGuide2009.pdf |title=U.S. Army Aviation Center of Excellence and Fort Rucker: The Home of Army Aviation |access-date=12 March 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100216093637/http://www.rucker.army.mil/pdf/InstallationGuide2009.pdf |archive-date=16 February 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n*In the TV-series [[The A-Team]] (1983\u201387), the fictional character of Army [[Captain (United States O-3)|Captain]] [[Howling Mad Murdock]] wears the [[Shoulder sleeve insignia (United States Army)|shoulder sleeve insignia]] of the 1st Aviation Brigade in the episode \"A Nice Place to Visit\".\n*In the 2017 movie, [[Kong: Skull Island]] the U.S. Army Aviation unit assigned to support the scientific research team, wear the 1st Aviation Brigade patch on their jungle fatigues and flight suits.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Allen M. Burdett, Jr.]], commanded the 1st Aviation Brigade from 1969 to 1970 and Commanded the Army's Aviation Center of Excellence from 1970 to 1973.\n\n==Notes==\n\n{{Reflist|group=\"Note\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official|https://home.army.mil/rucker/index.php/units-tenants/1ab}}\n\n[[Category:Training brigades of the United States Army|001]]\n[[Category:Aviation Brigades of the United States Army|001]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in the 1960s|001]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name=1st Aviation Brigade\n| image=1AvnBdeSSI.gif\n| image_size = 150\n|caption=\n|country=[[United States]]\n|allegiance=[[United States Army]]\n|type=Aviation brigade\n|branch=\n|dates=1966-1973<BR>1977-present\n|specialization=[[Aviation]]\n|command_structure=[[United States Army Aviation Center of Excellence]]\n|size=[[Brigade#Army|Brigade]]\n|garrison=\n|nickname= \n|motto= \n|colors= \n|march= \n|mascot=\n|battles=\n|anniversaries=\n<!-- Commanders -->\n|current_commander=Colonel Tammy Baugh\n|current_commander_label=\n<!-- Insignia -->\n|identification_symbol=\n|identification_symbol_label=Distinctive unit insignia\n|identification_symbol_2=\n}}\n\nThe '''1st Aviation Brigade''' commands three distinctly different battalions\u2014the 1st Battalion, [[13th Aviation Regiment (United States)|13th Aviation Regiment]]; the 1st Battalion, [[145th Aviation Regiment]]; and the 2nd Battalion, 13th Aviation Regiment, the former Unmanned Aircraft Systems Training Battalion at [[Fort Huachuca]], Arizona.\n\n==Vietnam==\n\nThe 1st Aviation Brigade traces its origins to the [[Vietnam War]]. In April 1965 the U.S. Army Aviation Brigade (Provisional) was activated with the existing [[13th Aviation Battalion|13th]], [[14th Aviation Battalion|14th]], [[52nd Aviation Regiment (United States)|52nd]], and [[145th Aviation Battalion]]s,<ref group=\"Note\">September 24th, 1963 brought to a close the 45th Transportation Battalion and gave birth to the 145th Combat Aviation Battalion.</ref> already in South Vietnam, reporting to it. In August 1965 it became the [[12th Combat Aviation Brigade|12th Aviation Group]], which then doubled in size and was used to form the 1st Aviation Brigade in March 1966.<ref name=\"1AVNB\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.1stavnbde.com/|title=Portal - 1st Aviation Brigade - U.S. Army, Vietnam|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401212829/http://www.1stavnbde.com/|archive-date=1 April 2016|access-date=12 May 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Dunstan, in ''Vietnam Choppers'' writes that the numerous independent aviation companies deployed during the war's early years had become difficult to move between sectors because they had developed 'individual means of operating in conjunction with the formations they supported.'<ref>{{cite book |last1=Dunstan |first1=Simon |title=Vietnam choppers: helicopters in battle 1950-1975 |date=2003 |publisher=Osprey Publishing |isbn=0850455723 |page=37}}</ref> Thus the brigade was formed to achieve standardization.\n\nBrigadier General [[George P. Seneff]], the Staff Aviation Officer at [[Military Assistance Command, Vietnam]] (MACV), became the brigade commander. Because the requirements varied in each part of Vietnam, the brigade tried to collocate one assault helicopter company with each U.S. brigade and in course of time each Republic of Korea brigade.<ref name=1AVNB /> The companies supporting [[Army of the Republic of Vietnam]] units were located in centralized positions to best provide support. The brigade assigned one combat aviation battalion headquarters in direct support of each infantry division and this battalion headquarters normally worked with that division no matter how many companies might be assigned for a specific mission. The Brigade [[Headquarters and headquarters company (United States)|Headquarters and Headquarters Company]] was located in Saigon from May 1966 until August 1967.  Then the HQ moved to [[Long Binh Post|Long Binh]] where it remained until Long Binh was closed in the early autumn of 1972. The HQ then moved to the MACV compound at [[Tan Son Nhut]], where it stayed until withdrawal.\n\nAt this time the 52nd Aviation Battalion supported the [[4th Infantry Division (United States)|4th Infantry Division]] in the highlands, the 10th Aviation Battalion supported the brigade of the 101st and the Republic of Korea division, the 11th Combat Aviation Battalion supported the [[1st Infantry Division (United States)|1st Infantry Division]], the 214th\u2014the 9th Division, and the [[269th Aviation Battalion]]\u2014the 25th Division. The 13th Battalion, which was later to become a full group, remained in the [[Mekong Delta]]. Two aviation groups\u2014the [[17th Aviation Brigade (United States)|17th]] and the 12th\u2014supervised the aviation assets in the [[II Corps (South Vietnam)|II]] and [[III Corps (South Vietnam)|III Corps Tactical Zone]]s respectively. The aviation group commander was also the aviation officer for the U.S. Field Force commander.\n\nDuring June 1970, the 1st Aviation Brigade reached its largest size, at which point it contained four combat aviation groups, 16 combat aviation battalions, and 83 companies totaling over 4,000 aircraft and 27,000 personnel.<ref group=\"Note\">Constituted 25 April 1966 in the Regular Army as Headquarters and Headquarters Company, 222d Aviation Battalion. Activated 25 May 1966 in Vietnam.</ref> The 34th General Support Group (Aviation Maintenance and Supply) was transferred to the control of 1st Aviation Brigade in November 1971 where it continued in operation well into 1972. On the signing of the cease-fire on 28 January 1973, the Brigade strength had been reduced to 5,000 personnel and 420 aircraft in four combat aviation groups. The brigade was returned to Fort Rucker, Alabama, on 24 March 1973, and was deactivated on 6 April 1973.\n\nAccording to Shelby Stanton's ''Vietnam Order of Battle,'' subordinate brigade units in Vietnam included:<ref>Stanton, ''Vietnam Order of Battle'', 1987, 109.</ref>\n*[[11th Expeditionary Combat Aviation Brigade|11th]], [[12th Combat Aviation Brigade|12th]], [[16th Combat Aviation Brigade (United States)|16th]], [[17th Aviation Brigade (United States)|17th]], [[101st Aviation Brigade (United States)|160th]], [[165th Aviation Group]]s\n*the [[164th Aviation Group]] was activated from the assets of a Provisional Aviation Group in the [[IV Corps (South Vietnam)|IV Corps Tactical Zone]] in 1968, and was located at [[Can Tho]] throughout its time in Vietnam. Its heritage appears to be carried out, since 1995, by the [[164th Theater Airfield Operations Group]] at [[Fort Rucker]]. \n*[[10th Aviation Regiment (United States)|10th]], [[11th Aviation Battalion|11th]], [[13th Aviation Battalion|13th]], [[14th Aviation Battalion|14th]], [[52nd Aviation Regiment (United States)|52nd]], [[58th Aviation Battalion|58th]], [[145th Aviation Battalion|145th]], [[210th Aviation Regiment (United States)|210th]], [[212th Aviation Battalion|212th]], [[214th Aviation Regiment (United States)|214th]], [[222nd Aviation Regiment (United States)|222nd]], [[223rd Aviation Battalion|223rd]], [[268th Aviation Battalion|268th]], [[269th Aviation Battalion|269th]],<ref>Note the 187 Aslt Hel Co served with this battalion March 1967-Apr 1971, before being transferred to the 11th Avn Bn., with which it served Apr 1971-14 Feb 72, inactivated that day. Stanton, Vietnam Order of Battalion, 113, 119.</ref> [[307th Aviation Battalion|307th]], [[308th Aviation Battalion]]s\n*PHANTOM, DELTA, CAPITAL, I Corps, BUFFALO Aviation Battalions (Provisional)\n*7th Squadron, [[1st Cavalry Regiment (United States)|1st Cavalry Regiment]], 1st Squadron, 9th Cavalry, 3-17, 7-17 Cavalry, all Air Cavalry Squadrons\n\n==Training formation==\n\nOn 18 February 1977 the brigade was reactivated at Fort Rucker as a training formation.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Williams |first1=James W |title=A History of Army Aviation |date=September 2005 |publisher=iUniverse |isbn=9780595810369 |page=136}}</ref>\n\nFamed [[Vietnam War]] combat veteran [[John Bahnsen]] commanded the 1st Aviation Brigade in the late 1970s and early 1980s.<ref>U.S. Army Aviation Center, [https://books.google.com/books?ei=4jjSUZraD4q80QGzw4C4Bw&id=MborAAAAYAAJ&dq=1st+aviation+brigade+bahnsen&q=bahnsen#search_anchor United States Army Aviation Digest], 1980, page 26</ref>\n\nThe 1st Aviation Brigade\u2019s primary mission has been to train and develop future aviation warfighting leaders. Including the lessons learned from deployed units, instructors and students write, review, and coordinate Army Aviation combined arms doctrine for aviation units below brigade level.\n\nThe course curriculum consists of a wide range of professional military education subjects, with emphasis on combined arms battlefield integration. The tactical training is further reinforced with state-of-the-art simulation, allowing students to assume various command and staff positions at all command levels while fighting simulated battles throughout a wide spectrum of tactical scenarios. Equally important is the initial entry training (IET) taught to entry level Aviation Branch Soldiers. IET teaches fundamental skills for U.S. Army personnel to perform their occupational specialties in an aviation unit.<ref name=\"rucker.army.mil\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.rucker.army.mil/pdf/InstallationGuide2009.pdf |title=U.S. Army Aviation Center of Excellence and Fort Rucker: The Home of Army Aviation |access-date=12 March 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100216093637/http://www.rucker.army.mil/pdf/InstallationGuide2009.pdf |archive-date=16 February 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n*In the TV-series [[The A-Team]] (1983\u201387), the fictional character of Army [[Captain (United States O-3)|Captain]] [[Howling Mad Murdock]] wears the [[Shoulder sleeve insignia (United States Army)|shoulder sleeve insignia]] of the 1st Aviation Brigade in the episode \"A Nice Place to Visit\".\n*In the 2017 movie, [[Kong: Skull Island]] the U.S. Army Aviation unit assigned to support the scientific research team, wear the 1st Aviation Brigade patch on their jungle fatigues and flight suits.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Allen M. Burdett, Jr.]], commanded the 1st Aviation Brigade from 1969 to 1970 and Commanded the Army's Aviation Center of Excellence from 1970 to 1973.\n\n==Notes==\n\n{{Reflist|group=\"Note\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{official|https://home.army.mil/rucker/index.php/units-tenants/1ab}}\n\n[[Category:Aviation Brigades of the United States Army|001]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in the 1960s|001]]\n", "name_user": "EpicDream86", "label": "safe", "comment": "add category", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1st_Aviation_Brigade"}
{"title_page": "Tom Fogerty", "text_new": "{{short description|American musician, best known as the rhythm guitarist in Creedence Clearwater Revival}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist \n| name            = Tom Fogerty\n| image           = Tom Fogerty.jpg\n| caption         = Tom Fogerty, 1974\n| background      = solo_singer \n| birth_name      = Thomas Richard Fogerty\n| birth_date      = {{birth date|1941|11|09|mf=y}}\n| birth_place     = [[Berkeley, California]], U.S.\n| death_date      = {{death date and age|1990|9|6|1941|11|9}}\n| death_place     = [[Scottsdale, Arizona]], U.S.\n| alias           = Rann Wild{{sfn|Bordowitz|1998|p=28}}\n| genre           = [[Rock music|Rock]], [[roots rock]], {{nowrap|[[country rock]]}}, [[blues rock]], [[swamp pop|swamp rock]], [[Southern rock]], [[rock and roll]]\n| occupation      = Musician, songwriter\n| instrument      = Guitar, vocals\n| associated_acts = [[Creedence Clearwater Revival]], [[Ruby (rock band)|Ruby]], [[The Blue Velvets]], [[The Golliwogs]]\n| label           = [[Fantasy Records|Fantasy]], PBR\n| years_active    = 1958\u20131990\n| website         = {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071018011505/http://www.geocities.com/julianforjudge/tomfogerty |date=October 18, 2007 |title=Tom Fogerty homepage }}\n}}\n\n'''Thomas Richard Fogerty''' (November 9, 1941 \u2013 September 6, 1990) was an American musician, best known as the rhythm guitarist, and one of the \nfounding member of [[Creedence Clearwater Revival]].<ref name=\"Larkin\">{{cite book|title=[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music|The Virgin Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]|editor=[[Colin Larkin (writer)|Colin Larkin]]|publisher=[[Virgin Books]]|date=1997|edition=Concise|isbn=1-85227-745-9|page=476}}</ref> He was posthumously inducted into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] in 1993.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rockhall.com/inductees/creedence-clearwater-revival |title=Creedence Clearwater Revival &#124; Rock & Roll Hall of Fame |website=Rockhall.com |date=1990-09-06 |accessdate=2017-04-26}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nTom Fogerty was born in [[Berkeley, California]], United States.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/> He began singing [[rock and roll]] in high school. He and his younger brother, [[John Fogerty|John]], had separate groups. Tom's band, Spider Webb and the Insects (which featured Jeremy Levine of [[the Seeds]]), signed a [[recording contract]] with [[Del-Fi Records]] but broke up in 1959 before releasing any [[Gramophone record|records]]. [[The Blue Velvets]]&mdash;a group led by John&mdash;began backing Tom. Eventually Tom joined the band, and the group recorded three singles (with Tom on lead vocals) for Orchestra Records in 1961 and 1962. By the mid 1960s, the group had been renamed The Golliwogs and were recording with [[Fantasy Records]], with Tom and John sharing lead vocal duties.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/> In 1968, the band was again renamed&mdash;this time to [[Creedence Clearwater Revival]]&mdash;and John had become full-time lead singer and primary songwriter.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/> During the few years of the life of CCR, Tom sang backing vocals and wrote songs, but only one of his songs from when CCR was named [[the Golliwogs]] (\"Walking on the Water\") was re-recorded and chosen to be put on CCR's debut album. This lack of vocal and songwriting opportunity, along with festering, long-standing animosity with his brother, led him to leave the band in early 1971, after finishing the recording of ''[[Pendulum (Creedence Clearwater Revival album)|Pendulum]]''.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/>\n\nAfter leaving the band, Fogerty began performing and recording as a solo artist.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/> He had minor hits like \"[[Goodbye Media Man]]\", \"Cast The First Stone\", \"Joyful Resurrection\", and \"B.A.R.T\". He remained with [[Fantasy Records]] and his 1971 solo debut album, ''[[Tom Fogerty (album)|Tom Fogerty]]'', reached #78 on the [[Billboard 200]] chart. On the follow-up, ''[[Excalibur (Tom Fogerty album)|Excalibur]]'', [[Jerry Garcia]] and [[Merl Saunders]] played on the sessions.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/> [[Stu Cook]] and [[Doug Clifford]] (CCR's former bass guitarist and drummer) as well as John Fogerty performed on the 1974 follow-up album, ''[[Zephyr National]]''. The song \"Joyful Resurrection\" features a complete reunion of CCR though John Fogerty recorded his parts separately. Cook and Clifford also backed Tom on his second LP release of 1974 titled ''[[Myopia (Tom Fogerty album)|Myopia]]''.\n\nThroughout the rest of the 1970s and 1980s, Tom Fogerty continued to record.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/> He claimed all royalties from the CCR period and sued Fantasy Records. Later, Tom re-signed with Fantasy. At the October 1980 reception for Tom's marriage to Tricia Clapper, all four members of CCR reunited and performed for the first time in a decade. They took the stage once more for a final time at a school reunion three years later. Tom Fogerty lived in [[Scottsdale, Arizona]], for the remainder of his life.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/>\n\n==Death==\nAt some point in the 1980s, Fogerty underwent back surgery, and was given a blood transfusion which was not screened for [[HIV]]. This caused him to become infected with HIV. This led to AIDS, with the ensuing complication of tuberculosis, which led to his death on September 6, 1990.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Tom Fogerty, Guitarist, 48 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/09/15/obituaries/tom-fogerty-guitarist-48.html |accessdate=8 December 2019 |work=New York Times |agency=Associated Press |date=September 15, 1990|page=29}}</ref> After his death, a music compilation titled ''[[The Very Best of Tom Fogerty]]'' was released.\n\n==Discography==\n{{See also|Creedence Clearwater Revival discography}}\n* ''[[Tom Fogerty (album)|Tom Fogerty]]'' (1972)\n* ''[[Excalibur (Tom Fogerty album)|Excalibur]]'' (1972)\n* ''[[Zephyr National]]'' (1974)\n* ''[[Myopia (Tom Fogerty album)|Myopia]]'' (1974)\n* ''[[Deal It Out]]'' (1981)\n* ''[[Sidekicks (album)|Sidekicks]]''  <small>(with Randy Oda)</small> (released posthumously in 1992)\n* ''[[The Very Best of Tom Fogerty]]'' (1999)\n\n;with Ruby\n* ''[[Ruby (Ruby album)|Ruby]]'' (1976)\n* ''[[Rock & Roll Madness]]'' (1978)\n* ''[[Precious Gems]]'' (1984)\n\n;Other appearances\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Artist\n!Album\n!Comment\n|-\n|rowspan=3|1972\n|[[Merle Saunders]]\n|''[[Fire Up Plus|Heavy Turbulence]]''\n|Guitar and vocals\n|-\n|[[Walter Hawkins]]\n|''Do Your Best''\n|Producer\n|-\n|[[Jim Post]]\n|''Slow To 20''\n|Backing vocals on \"Homemade Music\"\n|-\n|1973\n|rowspan=2|Merle Saunders\n|''[[Fire Up Plus|Fire Up]]''\n|Guitar and producer\n|-\n|1997\n|''Keepers''\n|Previously unreleased recordings\n|}\n\n==Citations==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{Cite book|first=Hank|last=Bordowitz|title=Bad Moon Rising: The Unauthorized History of Creedence Clearwater Revival|publisher=[[Chicago Review Press]]|year=2007|isbn=978-1556526619}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Allmusic|id=artist/tom-fogerty-mn0000606814|label=Tom Fogerty}}\n\n{{Tom Fogerty}}\n{{Creedence}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fogerty, Tom}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:1990 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century deaths from tuberculosis]]\n[[Category:AIDS-related deaths in Arizona]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:American rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:Creedence Clearwater Revival members]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from California]]\n[[Category:John Fogerty]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Berkeley, California]]\n[[Category:People from Contra Costa County, California]]\n[[Category:Rhythm guitarists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American musician, best known as the rhythm guitarist in Creedence Clearwater Revival}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist \n| name            = Tom Fogerty\n| image           = Tom Fogerty.jpg\n| caption         = Tom Fogerty, 1974\n| background      = solo_singer \n| birth_name      = Thomas Richard Fogerty\n| birth_date      = {{birth date|1941|11|09|mf=y}}\n| birth_place     = [[Berkeley, California]], U.S.\n| death_date      = {{death date and age|1990|9|6|1941|11|9}}\n| death_place     = [[Scottsdale, Arizona]], U.S.\n| alias           = Rann Wild{{sfn|Bordowitz|1998|p=28}}\n| genre           = [[Rock music|Rock]], [[roots rock]], {{nowrap|[[country rock]]}}, [[blues rock]], [[swamp pop|swamp rock]], [[Southern rock]], [[rock and roll]]\n| occupation      = Musician, songwriter\n| instrument      = Guitar, vocals\n| associated_acts = [[Creedence Clearwater Revival]], [[Ruby (rock band)|Ruby]], [[The Blue Velvets]], [[The Golliwogs]]\n| label           = [[Fantasy Records|Fantasy]], PBR\n| years_active    = 1958\u20131990\n| website         = {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071018011505/http://www.geocities.com/julianforjudge/tomfogerty |date=October 18, 2007 |title=Tom Fogerty homepage }}\n}}\n\n'''Thomas Richard Fogerty''' (November 9, 1941 \u2013 September 6, 1990) was an American musician, best known as the rhythm guitarist for [[Creedence Clearwater Revival]].<ref name=\"Larkin\">{{cite book|title=[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music|The Virgin Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]|editor=[[Colin Larkin (writer)|Colin Larkin]]|publisher=[[Virgin Books]]|date=1997|edition=Concise|isbn=1-85227-745-9|page=476}}</ref> He was posthumously inducted into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] in 1993.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rockhall.com/inductees/creedence-clearwater-revival |title=Creedence Clearwater Revival &#124; Rock & Roll Hall of Fame |website=Rockhall.com |date=1990-09-06 |accessdate=2017-04-26}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nTom Fogerty was born in [[Berkeley, California]], United States.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/> He began singing [[rock and roll]] in high school. He and his younger brother, [[John Fogerty|John]], had separate groups. Tom's band, Spider Webb and the Insects (which featured Jeremy Levine of [[the Seeds]]), signed a [[recording contract]] with [[Del-Fi Records]] but broke up in 1959 before releasing any [[Gramophone record|records]]. [[The Blue Velvets]]&mdash;a group led by John&mdash;began backing Tom. Eventually Tom joined the band, and the group recorded three singles (with Tom on lead vocals) for Orchestra Records in 1961 and 1962. By the mid 1960s, the group had been renamed The Golliwogs and were recording with [[Fantasy Records]], with Tom and John sharing lead vocal duties.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/> In 1968, the band was again renamed&mdash;this time to [[Creedence Clearwater Revival]]&mdash;and John had become full-time lead singer and primary songwriter.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/> During the few years of the life of CCR, Tom sang backing vocals and wrote songs, but only one of his songs from when CCR was named [[the Golliwogs]] (\"Walking on the Water\") was re-recorded and chosen to be put on CCR's debut album. This lack of vocal and songwriting opportunity, along with festering, long-standing animosity with his brother, led him to leave the band in early 1971, after finishing the recording of ''[[Pendulum (Creedence Clearwater Revival album)|Pendulum]]''.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/>\n\nAfter leaving the band, Fogerty began performing and recording as a solo artist.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/> He had minor hits like \"[[Goodbye Media Man]]\", \"Cast The First Stone\", \"Joyful Resurrection\", and \"B.A.R.T\". He remained with [[Fantasy Records]] and his 1971 solo debut album, ''[[Tom Fogerty (album)|Tom Fogerty]]'', reached #78 on the [[Billboard 200]] chart. On the follow-up, ''[[Excalibur (Tom Fogerty album)|Excalibur]]'', [[Jerry Garcia]] and [[Merl Saunders]] played on the sessions.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/> [[Stu Cook]] and [[Doug Clifford]] (CCR's former bass guitarist and drummer) as well as John Fogerty performed on the 1974 follow-up album, ''[[Zephyr National]]''. The song \"Joyful Resurrection\" features a complete reunion of CCR though John Fogerty recorded his parts separately. Cook and Clifford also backed Tom on his second LP release of 1974 titled ''[[Myopia (Tom Fogerty album)|Myopia]]''.\n\nThroughout the rest of the 1970s and 1980s, Tom Fogerty continued to record.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/> He claimed all royalties from the CCR period and sued Fantasy Records. Later, Tom re-signed with Fantasy. At the October 1980 reception for Tom's marriage to Tricia Clapper, all four members of CCR reunited and performed for the first time in a decade. They took the stage once more for a final time at a school reunion three years later. Tom Fogerty lived in [[Scottsdale, Arizona]], for the remainder of his life.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/>\n\n==Death==\nAt some point in the 1980s, Fogerty underwent back surgery, and was given a blood transfusion which was not screened for [[HIV]]. This caused him to become infected with HIV. This led to AIDS, with the ensuing complication of tuberculosis, which led to his death on September 6, 1990.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Tom Fogerty, Guitarist, 48 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/09/15/obituaries/tom-fogerty-guitarist-48.html |accessdate=8 December 2019 |work=New York Times |agency=Associated Press |date=September 15, 1990|page=29}}</ref> After his death, a music compilation titled ''[[The Very Best of Tom Fogerty]]'' was released.\n\n==Discography==\n{{See also|Creedence Clearwater Revival discography}}\n* ''[[Tom Fogerty (album)|Tom Fogerty]]'' (1972)\n* ''[[Excalibur (Tom Fogerty album)|Excalibur]]'' (1972)\n* ''[[Zephyr National]]'' (1974)\n* ''[[Myopia (Tom Fogerty album)|Myopia]]'' (1974)\n* ''[[Deal It Out]]'' (1981)\n* ''[[Sidekicks (album)|Sidekicks]]''  <small>(with Randy Oda)</small> (released posthumously in 1992)\n* ''[[The Very Best of Tom Fogerty]]'' (1999)\n\n;with Ruby\n* ''[[Ruby (Ruby album)|Ruby]]'' (1976)\n* ''[[Rock & Roll Madness]]'' (1978)\n* ''[[Precious Gems]]'' (1984)\n\n;Other appearances\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Artist\n!Album\n!Comment\n|-\n|rowspan=3|1972\n|[[Merle Saunders]]\n|''[[Fire Up Plus|Heavy Turbulence]]''\n|Guitar and vocals\n|-\n|[[Walter Hawkins]]\n|''Do Your Best''\n|Producer\n|-\n|[[Jim Post]]\n|''Slow To 20''\n|Backing vocals on \"Homemade Music\"\n|-\n|1973\n|rowspan=2|Merle Saunders\n|''[[Fire Up Plus|Fire Up]]''\n|Guitar and producer\n|-\n|1997\n|''Keepers''\n|Previously unreleased recordings\n|}\n\n==Citations==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{Cite book|first=Hank|last=Bordowitz|title=Bad Moon Rising: The Unauthorized History of Creedence Clearwater Revival|publisher=[[Chicago Review Press]]|year=2007|isbn=978-1556526619}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Allmusic|id=artist/tom-fogerty-mn0000606814|label=Tom Fogerty}}\n\n{{Tom Fogerty}}\n{{Creedence}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fogerty, Tom}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:1990 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century deaths from tuberculosis]]\n[[Category:AIDS-related deaths in Arizona]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:American rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:Creedence Clearwater Revival members]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from California]]\n[[Category:John Fogerty]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Berkeley, California]]\n[[Category:People from Contra Costa County, California]]\n[[Category:Rhythm guitarists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n", "name_user": "2604:2000:610b:4600:b4c6:2092:789e:4a40", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom_Fogerty"}
{"title_page": "Christopher Plummer filmography", "text_new": "{{See also|List of awards and nominations received by Christopher Plummer}}\n[[File:Christopher Plummer 1964.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Plummer in 1964]]\n[[Christopher Plummer]] (born December 13, 1929) is a [[Cinema of Canada|Canadian]] film, television and stage actor. On stage, Plummer's most notable roles are that of Cyrano de Bergerac in ''[[Cyrano (musical)|Cyrano]]'' (1974) and as [[John Barrymore]] in ''[[Barrymore (play)|Barrymore]]''. He won the [[Tony Award for Best Actor in a Play]] for these two roles. On film, Plummer is known for portraying [[Georg von Trapp|Captain von Trapp]] in ''[[The Sound of Music (film)|The Sound of Music]]'' (1965).<ref name=\"Plummer\">{{cite news| url=http://www.boston.com/ae/movies/articles/2010/01/31/at_80_christopher_plummer_lands_roles_that_are_his_cup_of_tea/?page=all| title=At 80, Plummer has arrived at his 'Station'| work=The Boston Globe | date=January 31, 2010| author=Judy Abel| accessdate=July 25, 2012}}</ref> He also appeared in ''[[Waterloo (1970 film)|Waterloo]]'' (1970), ''[[The Man Who Would Be King (film)|The Man Who Would Be King]]'' (1975), ''[[The Insider (film)|The Insider]]'' (1999), as [[Leo Tolstoy]] in ''[[The Last Station]]'' (2009) and as [[J. Paul Getty]] in ''[[All the Money in the World]]'' (2017).\n\nPlummer provided the voice of antagonist Charles F. Muntz in the [[Pixar]] animated film ''[[Up (2009 film)|Up]]'' (2009).<ref name=time>{{cite news|last=Corliss|first=Richard|title=Up, Up and Away: Another New High for Pixar|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1896737,00.html|accessdate=November 22, 2013|newspaper=Time|date=May 28, 2009|authorlink=Richard Corliss}}</ref>\n\nPlummer won an [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]] for his performance in [[Mike Mills (director)|Mike Mills]]' film ''[[Beginners]]'' (2010).\n\n==Performances==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! No